<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Report Details CPPCC's Foreign Activities in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2502190394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1456 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed "Roundup": "CPPCC National Committee Promotes </F>
International Exchanges"] 
  [Text] Beijing, February 25 (XINHUA) -- Last year Li 
Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese 
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), paid 
official visits to Nepal, India and Pakistan. 
  His visits marked the peak of increasingly active exchanges 
and cooperation between the CPPCC National Committee and 
parliaments and mass organizations in other countries over the 
past year. 
  This is the first time for the chairman of the National 
Committee of the CPPCC, the largest united front organization in 
China, to visit other countries since the founding of New China 
in 1949. 
  During his visits, Chairman Li Ruihuan briefed the leaders 
of 
the three countries and people from all walks of life on China's 
foreign policy, and its multi-party cooperation and political 
consultation system under the leadership of the Chinese 
Communist Party, promoting exchanges and cooperation between the 
CPPCC National Committee and parliaments in the three countries. 
  Public sentiments overseas confirm that Li's visits 
represent 
the CPPCC National Committee's dual role in expanding both 
governmental and non-governmental exchanges in the diplomatic 
area. 
  Established 45 years ago, the CPPCC National Committee 
consists of various non-communist parties and mass organizations 
and is considered a creation for enhancing socialist democracy 
in China. It plays a significant role in political consultation 
and democratic supervision in managing state affairs. 
  International exchanges held by the CPPCC National Committee 
in 1993 were characterized by frequent visits to other countries 
by the committee's leaders. 
  Also in 1993, Ye Xuanping, Wu Xueqian, Seypidin Azizi, Hong 
Xuezhi, Hu Sheng and Sun Fuling, vice-chairmen of the CPPCC 
National Committee, paid separate visits to Vietnam, Laos, 
Thailand, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, Syria, 
Oman, Qatar and Bahrain. 
  During their talks with the leaders of these countries, 
these 
vice-chairmen reiterated China's consistent stand in support of 
the just cause of the people in developing countries and 
expounded the positions of the Chinese Government concerning the 
international situation and regional conflicts. 
  Furthermore, they also explained to their guests the role of 
the CPPCC organizations in a bid to expand cooperation with 
parliaments and mass organizations in other countries. 
  To date, the CPPCC National Committee has forged cooperative 
relationships with 46 organizations in 36 countries. 
  The committee focuses its international exchanges and 
cooperation on China's economic construction. Various 
subcommittees also try to expand cooperation with economists and 
scientists overseas. 
  For example, while visiting Britain in 1993, members of a 
delegation sent by the subcommittee of science and technology 
concentrated on learning how scientific and technological 
findings were applied to industrial production. 
  Moreover, they discussed with their British colleagues the 
relationship between scientific research and social progress, in 
an effort to draw on useful experience to perfect the policy 
governing the development of science and technology in China. 
  Also in 1993, leaders of the CPPCC National Committee 
received 250 leaders of overseas Chinese organizations in 
Britain, France, Germany, Japan, the Netherlands, the 
Philippines and the United States. 
  This year the committee will continue to expand cooperation 
and exchanges with parliaments in other countries. It will also 
organize specialized groups to visit foreign countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

