<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhu Rongji Meets Japanese Economic Figures, Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets Businessmen </H4>
<F P=102> OW2502173894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1611 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2502173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, February 25 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice Premier 
Zhu Rongji said here today the ongoing reform in China will push 
forward bilateral cooperation between Tokyo and Beijing, Chinese 
Foreign Ministry officials said. 
  Zhu said China and Japan have gained "a historical 
opportunity" to further develop ties as China is now striving 
for a shift to market economy from the traditional planed 
economy, the officials said. 
  He made the remarks when he was lunching with Yoshio 
Sakurauchi, head of the Japanese Association for the Promotion 
of International Trade. 
  The vice premier spoke highly of the association for having 
made "precious contributions" to the strengthening of Japan's 
trade and economic ties with China, they said. 
  In a separate meeting, Zhu briefed a group of leading 
Japanese bankers on the current economic situation in China and 
its reforms on finance and taxation. 
  In the evening, he dined with leaders from six organizations 
for Japan-China friendship and called on them to continue their 
efforts to help solidify bilateral relations, the officials said. 
  Earlier in the day, he met Japan's International Trade and 
Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai, State Minister for Economic 
Planning Manae Kubota and former Foreign Minister Michio 
Watanabe. 
  Zhu arrived here Wednesday [23 February] for a nine-day 
visit. He is leaving Tokyo Saturday for western and southwestern 
Japan to take a first-hand look at corporate activities there. 

</TEXT>

