<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhu Rongji Meets Japanese Economic Figures, Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets With Japanese Business Leaders </H4>
<F P=102> OW2702022494 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0757 
GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2702022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Zhang Huanli (1728 3562 0448)] </F>
  [Text] Tokyo, 26 Feb (XINHUA) -- This morning Zhu Rongji, 
vice premier of China's State Council, was invited to attend a 
breakfast hosted by Japan's Mitsui group in his honor. 
  Zhu Rongji said: You all are old friends of the Chinese 
people and well-established Japanese entrepreneurs. I can tell 
you that China's economic reform is bound to succeed, and China 
will maintain its annual economic growth rate at 8 to 9 percent 
for a long time to come. You should have full confidence in it. 
  Zhu Rongji added emphatically: Favorable temporal, 
geographical, human, and other factors bind China and Japan 
closely together. Friendly relations and cooperation between 
China and Japan are an irresistible historical trend. China 
needs Japan's capital and technology for its development, 
whereas Japan needs China's markets and resources for its 
economic development. Only by increasing cooperation can China 
and Japan achieve their own prosperity. In conducting equal and 
mutually beneficial cooperation, China and Japan should show 
mutual understanding, consult with each other in a friendly 
manner, and solve existing problems. 
  Zhu Rongji expressed the hope that Japan's economic circles 
would consider the overall interest in developing Sino-Japanese 
cooperation and work with China in constantly advancing 
good-neighbor and friendly relations between China and Japan. 
His speech won warm applause from those present at the 
breakfast. 
  Prominent Japanese entrepreneurs attending the breakfast 
included Naohiko Kumagaya, president of Mitsui &amp; Co., Ltd.; 
Yosuo Matsushita, president of Sakura Bank; Joichi Aoi, 
president of Toshiba Corporation; Katsunosuke Maeda, president 
of Toray Industries; and Yoshiro Sasaki, vice president of 
Nippon Steel Corporation. They related their experiences in 
developing economic relations and trade with China, spoke highly 
of China's achievements in economic reform, and repeatedly 
expressed their wish to vigorously promote cooperation with 
China. 
  He Chunlin, deputy secretary general of the State Council, 
and other key aides attended the breakfast. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

