<H3> <TI>   UN Inspectors Granted Visas To Visit DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2702024594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0227 GMT 27 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2702024594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, February 26 (XINHUA) -- Inspectors of the 
International Atomic Energy Agency were granted today visas to 
visit the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), 
according to a news bulletin released by the agency. 
  The bulletin said the group of inspectors were scheduled to 
arrive in Pyongyang on March 1, and then visit seven nuclear 
facilities in the country. 
  DPRK agreed on February 15 to open the seven nuclear 
facilities, but said two other facilities were not included. 
  The U.N. agency urged DPRK on February 23 to grant visas to 
the inspectors as soon as possible and set a one-week deadline. 
  In a related development, the United States agreed to cancel 
joint military exercises this year with South Korea and to begin 
the third round of DPRK-U.S. talks on March 21 in Geneva. 
  The two sides also agreed that the working-level contacts 
between the North and South should resume in Panmunjom. 

</TEXT>

