<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ramos Appoints New Finance Secretary </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK3101120194 Manila MANILA STANDARD in English 27 Jan 94 p 12 </F>
<F P=103> BK3101120194 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila MANILA STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Ramos yesterday appointed Development 
Bank of the Philippines (DBP) Chairman Roberto de Ocampo as 
acting finance secretary replacing Ernest Leung effective 1 
February 1994. Ocampo's designation to the powerful finance 
portfolio has been floated around for quite sometime. 
Apparently, Malacanang has received favorable feedbacks on him, 
especially from the business community. 
  The finance post was vacated in May 1993 when the nomination 
of then Finance Secretary Ramon del Rosario Jr. was rejected by 
the Commission on Appointments [CA]. Leung, a competent 
technical man who shuns publicly, was not keen on being named 
the permanent finance secretary, a Malacanang source said. 
  Leung has been an old hand in the finance department having 
served as assistant finance secretary during the Aquino 
administration. 
  President Ramos scouted for candidates for the finance 
portfolio from the private sector. But his efforts were 
unsuccessful because of the sad fate of Del Rosario at the hands 
of the CA. 
  The president appointed Leung to two important positions -- 
as president of the Philippine Deposit Insurance Corporation 
(PDIC) and chairman of the Central Bank board of liquidators 
effective 1 February 1994. 
  The Board of Liquidators has the task of disposing of the 
assets and liabilities of the old Central Bank. The president 
also designated DBP Vice Chairman Alfredo Antonio as officer in 
charge of the DBP, effective 1 February, said Ocampo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

