<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aftermath of Political Reform Accord Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   LDP, SDPJ Approve Compromise </H4>
<F P=102> OW2901060594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0553 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901060594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 29 KYODO -- The main opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and the Social Democratic Party 
[of Japan] (SDP) [SDPJ] on Saturday [29 January] endorsed a 
compromise over political reform reached between Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa and LDP President Yohei Kono, officials of the 
parties said. 
  The LDP reached the accord at a meeting of the highest 
decision-making body of the Executive Council and the SDPJ, the 
largest force in the seven-party ruling coalition, at a meeting 
of members of both houses of the Diet. 
  Hosokawa and Kono reached a basic accord Friday night in 
eleventh-hour talks to break the impasse over the 
government-proposed political reform bills on which Hosokawa had 
staked his political career. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

