</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aftermath of Political Reform Accord Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Lower House Passes Legislation </H4>
<F P=102> OW2901082194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0810 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 29 KYODO -- The House of 
Representatives on Saturday [29 January] approved the ruling 
coalition's political reform package whose key phases are set to 
be revised at the regular Diet session slated to convene on 
Monday. The two-tier arrangement on parliamentary proceedings 
was hammered out at an eleventh-hour, horse-trading session 
between Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and Liberal Democratic 
Party President Yohei Kono from Friday night to early Saturday. 
  The powerful lower chamber of Japan's two-chamber Diet gave 
its blessing to the legislation by a stand-up vote. 
  The seven parties of the ruling coalition and the main 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) endorsed the 
compromise. The opposition Japanese Communist Party voted 
against the package. 
  The legislation is almost certain to clear a subsequent 
House 
of Councillors session later in the day, the final day of the 
current extraordinary Diet session. 
  A date for implementation of the legislation was deleted 
from 
the government's original bills in line with the agreement 
between Hosokawa and Kono. The timing of the enforcement of the 
new law will be finalized through debate at the onset of the 
regular Diet session. 
  Earlier in the day, the joint committee of both houses of 
the 
Diet approved the compromise over political reform reached 
between Hosokawa and Kono. 
  The 20-legislator joint committee was set up after the upper 
house voted down the package on January 21, forcing the ruling 
coalition to mount desperate efforts to salvage the bills. The 
reform package passed the lower house on November 18. 
  After talks at the panel deadlocked, the stalemate was 
finally broken in top-level negotiations between Hosokawa and 
Kono. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

