<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa's Special Adviser Tanaka Steps Down </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101031894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0314 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101031894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 31 KYODO -- Shusei Tanaka, a special 
adviser to Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, leaves his post 
Monday [31 January] in line with a promise to step down 
following completion of the premier's top priority task of 
political reform, Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura 
said. 
  Tanaka earlier told Hosokawa that he would serve as special 
adviser until Diet debate on political reform ended, the top 
government spokesman told a news conference. 
  The government's political reform package, aimed at rooting 
out political graft, cleared the Diet on Saturday after Hosokawa 
and Yohei Kono, president of the main opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party, struck a deal on making modifications in the 
next regular Diet session. 
  Tanaka, the No. 2 man of Sakigake (Harbinger), a small 
component of Hosokawa's seven-party coalition, will concentrate 
on party affairs from now on, said Takemura, who heads Sakigake. 
He has pledged his continued support for Hosokawa, according to 
the chief cabinet secretary. 
  Takemura said Tanaka's resignation has nothing to do with 
his 
remarks last week suggesting Hosokawa would disband the cabinet 
and step down from power if his political reform bid ended in 
failure. 
  Tanaka, 53, has been elected to the House of Representatives 
three times from the No. 1 constituency of Nagano Prefecture. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

