<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Political Reform Job `Done' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101073694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0717 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101073694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 31 KYODO -- Shusei Tanaka stepped down 
Monday [31 January] as special adviser to Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa, saying his job of helping to enact political 
reform was done. 
  "I felt a great responsibility for having advocated a 
political reform government," Tanaka told reporters at the 
headquarters of Sakigake (Harbinger), a small component of 
Hosokawa's seven-party coalition government and a party to which 
he belongs. "I could not have quit if the political reform 
bills had not gone through," he said. "But I can step down with 
a stirring feeling because they were enacted." 
  Tanaka, 53, the No. 2 man of Sakigake, said his resignation 
is in line with an accord with Hosokawa that he would step down 
once Diet debate on political reform ends. 
  The government's political reform package cleared the Diet 
on 
Saturday after Hosokawa and Yohei Kono, president of the 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party, reached a compromise on its 
amendments in the next regular Diet session. 
  Hosokawa had staked his political fate on enactment by the 
Saturday close of the extraordinary Diet session. The measures 
are designed to clean up Japan's money driven political system 
and clamp curbs on political donations. 
  Saying it is now time to fulfill his duty as a Sakigake 
member to meet public expectations for the party, Tanaka 
expressed hope he can continue supporting Hosokawa from outside 
the government. 
  No one will take up the post of special adviser to the 
premier after Tanaka quits, Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi 
Takemura told a Monday morning news conference. 
  The Hosokawa administration's next main task should be 
administrative reform, Tanaka said, noting it is politicians, 
not bureaucrats, who should be responsible for the way policies 
are carried out. "I got the impression that the Diet has not 
played its role sufficiently in closely monitoring 
administrative authorities," he noted. 
  Tanaka has been elected to the House of Representatives 
three 
times from the No. 1 constituency of Nagano Prefecture. 

</TEXT>

