<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sources Discuss Government Budget Compilation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901053494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0522 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901053494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 29 KYODO -- The government and ruling 
coalition will convene a meeting of a newly created consultative 
body Saturday evening [29 January] upon passage through the Diet 
of four political reform bills to draft a package of stimulative 
economic measures and a budget for fiscal 1994 which starts in 
April, government sources said. 
  The consultative body, chaired by Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata, began discussions on the fiscal 1994 budget late last 
year. The debate was stalled earlier this month, however, due 
to political turmoil after the rejection of the reform bills by 
the House of Councillors January 21. 
  Friday's agreement on political reforms reached between 
Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and Yohei Kono, president of the main 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party, prompted the government and 
governing coalition to make haste in weaving together steps to 
rev up the flagging economy, the sources said. 
  The consultative body, made up of cabinet ministers in 
charge 
of economic affairs and representatives of the ruling coalition 
parties, is determined to set the timetable for drafting the 
national budget on Saturday, they said. 
  Saturday's discussion is expected to focus on when to raise 
the 3 percent consumption tax as a means of securing funds to 
implement major income and residential tax cuts, the sources 
said. 
  Indications are that the government will announce the 
pump-priming package by the end of next week and have the 
Ministry of Finance adopt its budget proposal around February 10 
ahead of a summit meeting between Hosokawa and U.S. President 
Bill Clinton in Washington February 11. 
  The government intends to adopt its draft budget in 
mid-February, sources said. 

</TEXT>

