<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Top Businessmen' Request Income Tax Cuts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901092394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0904 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 29 KYODO -- Top businessmen called on 
the coalition government of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa 
Saturday [29 January] to implement income tax cuts "as soon as 
possible" to prop up the faltering economy. The request 
followed the Diet's passage of four political reform bills 
earlier in the day as a result of a compromise accord reached 
between Hosokawa and Yohei Kono, president of the main 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party in a last-ditch meeting late 
Friday. 
  The attention of the business community now focuses on how 
speedily the Hosokawa administration will carry out economic 
stimulative measures. Business leaders by and large believe the 
foundation has been laid for stimulating the post-bubble, 
stagnant economy. 
  Hiroshi Saito, chairman of the Japan Iron and Steel 
Federation, noted the economy is now in critical shape. 
  "I strongly hope the government will draft a budget (for 
fiscal 1994) and implement pump-priming measures at the earliest 
possible time, including a substantial cut in income taxes," 
said Saito, also chairman of Nippon Steel Corp., the world's 
largest steel producer. The view was shared by Kohei Abe, head 
of the Federation of Electric Power Companies, who said he also 
wants the government to grapple with trade issues with the 
United States in a positive way ahead of a February 11 summit 
between Hosokawa and U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington. 
  Reiichi Yumikura, chairman of the Japan Chemical Fibers 
Association, said Hosokawa should take the leadership in 
reducing income taxes "retroactively and speedily." 
  Meanwhile, an executive of a major automaker expressed the 
view that Diet approval of the political reform program has made 
it possible for the coalition government of Prime Minister 
Hosokawa to bolster its power base. 
  "This in turn indicates Hosokawa may be able to exchange 
views frankly with Clinton on bilateral problems such as trade 
imbalances and the yen's ascent against the U.S. dollar," he 
said. 
  Japanese automakers, electronics companies and other 
export-oriented manufacturers have been badly hurt by the rapid 
appreciation of the yen in value which makes their products 
abroad more expensive. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

