<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Officials': Pump-Priming To Include Tax Cuts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901135194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1317 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 29 KYODO -- The coalition government of 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa plans to work out next week a 
new round of 15-16 trillion yen pump-priming measures that will 
include income tax cuts, officials said Saturday [29 January]. 
  The officials said the decision was made at a meeting of the 
Council on Economic Problems formed by the government and 
parties in the ruling coalition. "A decision (on the tax 
problem) will be made either Monday evening or Tuesday morning 
at the latest," Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister, told reporters. 
  Shortly after a compromise political reform program was 
passed by both houses of the Diet earlier Saturday, Hosokawa 
told a news conference that he has no plan at present to raise 
the consumption tax rate from the present 3 percent. 
  The officials said the council also decided to complete 
fiscal 1994 budget by February 15. 
  Manae Kubota, director general of the Economic Planning 
Agency, said it would be difficult to set any definite timing 
for a consumption tax hike in view of the current economic 
situation. 
  Government sources said the ruling coalition plans to carry 
out tax cuts totaling from 6 to 7 trillion yen, separate from a 
consumption tax increase. The sources said the proposed 
reduction, covering both income and local taxes, will be put 
into effect, retroactive to January 1, and deficit-covering 
national bonds would be issued to cover revenue shortfalls. 
  The sources said discussions at the economic council focused 
on how to raise funds for the tax cuts. 
  The Finance Ministry insists that the tax cuts be carried 
out 
in tandem with a hike in the consumption tax from the current 3 
percent to 7 percent around April 1995, the sources said. They 
said the ministry wants to use the revenue increase from the 
consumption tax hike to redeem national bonds to be issued for 
the income tax cuts. 
  The ruling parties, however, contend that measures to ease 
the tax burden on low income earners should be taken first, the 
sources said. They said discussions on the consumption tax hike 
will likely be carried over into fiscal 1996. 

</TEXT>

