<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura on Timing of Pump-Priming Announcement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3001095394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0929 GMT 30 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3001095394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Takamatsu, Jan. 30 KYODO -- The coalition 
government of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa plans to announce 
on Wednesday [2 February] or Thursday a comprehensive package of 
pump-priming measures to shore up the economy now in a prolonged 
slump, the top government spokesman said Sunday. Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Masayoshi Takemura did not reveal the size of the 
package. 
  Government sources say the business stimulating measures 
will 
total 15 to 16 trillion yen and will include 7 trillion yen in 
income and resident tax cuts. 
  Takemura said the cuts and revenue sources for them will be 
specified in the plan. The government and ruling coalition 
parties "will decide in the first half of this week on how big 
the income tax and resident tax cuts should be, whether 
corporate taxes can also be reduced and how to finance such tax 
cuts," he said. 
  Takemura spoke at a reception in Takamatsu, Shikoku Island, 
sponsored by his party, Sakigake (Harbinger). 
  Takemura, who is Hosokawa's chief spokesman and chief of 
staff, said many leaders of the coalition's seven parties share 
the view that the tax cuts should be implemented for a certain 
period of time before the consumption tax is raised from the 
present 3 percent. The Finance Ministry insists the cuts be 
carried out in tandem with a hike in the consumption tax to 7 
percent around April 1995, government sources say. 

</TEXT>

