<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii: Tax Cut, Hike To Go in Same Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101042094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0404 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101042094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 31 KYODO -- Finance Minister Hirohisa 
Fujii stressed the government's policy Monday [31 January] of 
implementing a cut in income tax and a rise in the consumption 
tax in a single package. He made the comment at a press meeting 
soon after consulting with Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura to confirm their 
remarks over the weekend indicating a revision of government 
policy. 
  He said he complained to Takemura over his remarks and said 
they made it difficult for him to fulfill his responsibilities 
as finance minister. 
  Fujii said he reiterated that under the government's basic 
policy of conducting the tax cut and hike as a single measure, a 
joint economic forum of the government and ruling parties is to 
decide on the tax issue "in two or three days." He said 
Takemura agreed and told him that news reports did not reflect 
his "real intention." He later saw Hosokawa, who also agreed 
with him. 
  Takemura had hinted at a reception hosted by his party, 
Sakigake, on Sunday, that there was a possibility of separating 
the tax hike and of issuing deficit-covering bonds to finance 
the tax cut. 
  Hosokawa told reporters Saturday that he was not considering 
a consumption tax hike. 
  Meanwhile, Fujii repeated his strong opposition to the 
issuance of "untreated" deficit-financing bonds, and called for 
the timing and other concrete details of a consumption tax hike 
to be stipulated in the same law as an income tax cut so as to 
guarantee repayment of bonds issued to cover the time lag 
between the tax cut and hike. 

</TEXT>

