<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Departments Disagree Over Growth Estimate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101110494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0938 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 31 KYODO -- Japanese Government offices 
are at odds over an economic growth projection for fiscal 1994, 
beginning on April 1, officials said Monday [31 January]. 
  The government is likely to set an official economic growth 
estimate around February 9 as a basis for its budget for the 
year. But the officials said the Finance Ministry, the Ministry 
of International Trade and Industry (MITI) and the Economic 
Planning Agency (EPA) disagree on growth predictions. 
  The Finance Ministry and MITI say the annual growth rate for 
gross domestic product (GDP) should be set at somewhere between 
2.5 and 3.0 percent, while the EPA says it should be slightly 
above 2 percent, the officials said. The estimate for fiscal 
1993 was 3.3 percent. 
  The three departments are scheduled to start ironing out 
their differences as soon as the government announces its new 
pump-priming package on Thursday, which is expected to feature 
major income tax cuts and additional public works spending. 
  EPA officials predicted the real economic growth rate for 
fiscal 1993, which ends March 31, will be slightly above zero, 
managing to stay in the plus column. They forecast the growth 
rate for fiscal 1994 will barely record 2 percent, even taking 
into account the effects of the new pump-priming package. 
  The Finance Ministry, however, says the growth estimate 
should be set at close to 3 percent so that the government will 
avoid issuing deficit-covering bonds other than those for 
offsetting tax cuts. The MITI hopes to set a similar growth 
target. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

