<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Radio Free Asia, Human Rights Criticized </TI></H3>
<H4>   NHAN DAN Condemns Senate Vote </H4>
<F P=102> BK3101062694 Hanoi VNA in English 0612 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK3101062694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi VNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi VNA Jan. 31 -- "The US Senate's decision to 
set up 'Radio Free Asia' completely runs counter to the trend 
for peace, stability and cooperation, violates international 
law, and blatantly interferes into Asian countries' internal 
affairs", says NHAN DAN paper in a commentary today. 
  The paper continues: 
  "Public opinions in Asian countries and even in the United 
States protest against the decision. Many people held that the 
setting up of 'Radio Free Asia' in the form of Cold War is no 
longer useful and suitable, especially when the economic 
relations between the US and Asia are increasing". 
  The paper recalls that spokespersons for the Foreign 
Ministries of Vietnam, China and Democratic People's Republic of 
Korea and Myanmar [Burma] have expressed their indignation 
against that move. 
  "Asia has emerged as a region of relative peace, stability, 
cooperation and dynamic development, the common aspiration of 
all nations in the region is to expand multilateral and 
diversified cooperation in order to defend peace, security and 
socio-economic development on the basis of mutual respect for 
independence and sovereignty, without interference into each 
other's affairs, and cooperation for equal benefit", the paper 
notes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

