<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul To Collect U.S. Embassy Building Rent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901055194 Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO in Korean 29 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901055194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The ROK Government has decided to collect rent from 
the United States for the use of the U.S. Embassy building for 
the last five years alone. The ROK Foreign, Finance, Defense, 
and Culture and Sports Ministries reached this decision at a 
joint meeting on 28 January. They also decided to hold 
consultations with the United States on this matter sooner or 
later. A ROK Government official said: "The government made 
such a decision because the period of prescription for rents 
stipulated in the Government Budget Account Law is five years." 
He also said: "The government decided to ask the United States 
to pay rent without fail if it continues to use the building." 
  The government made such a decision because the Board of 
Audit and Inspection last July pointed out that the "U.S. 
Government had not paid rent for the past 13 years with no 
justifiable reason." 
  The ROK and the United States agreed in 1960 that the United 
States would use the 6,615 square-meter eight-story building 
free of charge as long as the U.S. Operations Mission or its 
successor organization stays in the ROK." 
  However, the United States insists: The Economic Department 
of the U.S. Embassy inherited the role of the U.S. Agency for 
International Development to Korea, which was inaugurated as a 
result of the restructuring of the U.S. Operations Mission in 
1968 and which was abolished in 1980. Therefore, the U.S. 
Embassy has no reason to pay rent. Also, the 1962 agreement on 
the use of the building stipulates that the United States can 
use it free of charge as long as the ROK-U.S. Mutual Defense 
Treaty exists. So, the United States has the right to continue 
to use the building free of charge. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

