<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Envoy's Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3101005394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0006 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3101005394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 31 (YONHAP) -- Korean Ambassador to 
Washington Han Sung-su says he believes that the U.S. Government 
would not make a hasty decision on former presidential aide Kim 
Chong-hwi's application for permanent residency in the United 
States. 
  Han said on Sunday, however, he did not know the exact 
status 
of Kim Chong-hwi, former senior secretary for Foreign and 
National Security Affairs to President No Tae-u, in the United 
States. 
  Kim, wanted in South Korea on suspicion of accepting bribes 
in connection with the Yulgok military buildup program, was 
reported to have applied for permanent U.S. residency. 
  Han made the remark to reporters at Kimpo International 
Airport Sunday after he arrived from Washington to attend a 
conference of heads of diplomatic missions. 
  With regard to the North Korean nuclear problem Han said the 
issue will have to be referred to the U.N. Security Council if 
North Korea and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
fail to reach any agreement on IAEA inspection of North Korean 
nuclear facilities by Feb. 21. 
  Korean Ambassador to China Hwang Pyong-tae, who also arrived 
for the conference on Sunday, said that the Seoul government has 
informed North Korea through China that Pyongyang has to allow 
IAEA inspection by Feb. 21 when the IAEA convenes a meeting of 
Board of Directors in Vienna. 
  "I have been meeting responsible Chinese officials from time 
to time to discuss problems aimed at resolving the North Korean 
nuclear problem," Hwang added. 
  On the planned visit to China by President Kim Yong-sam, 
Hwang said the date is tentatively set for late March and 
preparations for it are progressing smoothly, Hwang said. 
  Since President Kim is going to visit China as a state 
guest, 
he will be meeting his Chinese counterpart Jiang Zemin and other 
top Chinese leaders, he said. 
  Commenting on the establishment of air routes to China, 
Hwang 
said the two countries will first set up a regular air route 
between Seoul and Beijing before starting to negotiate for an 
air route between Seoul and Shanghai. 
  Hwang said he hoped the air route question will be resolved 
by the time President Kim visits China. 

</TEXT>

