<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Return Rescued Soldiers to DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901101294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1006 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 29 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry on 
Saturday decided to return the two North Korean soldiers 
recently rescued in the West Sea to the North in accordance with 
their wish. 
  The two are Sfc. Kim Chol-chin, age 23, and Pvt. Kim 
Kyong-chol, 19, of a North Korean People's Constabulary Unit. 
  The duo were spotted and rescued unconscious on Jan. 27 
south 
of the West Sea extension of the Military Demarcation Line near 
Paengnyong-do Island while they were adrift in a tiny boat. 
  They were taken to the capital military hospital, where they 
expressed the hope to return to North Korea, a Ministry official 
said. 
  He said the two will be returned to North Korea through the 
Military Armistice Commission at Panmunjom inasmuch as they are 
military members and were rescued in an area under control of 
the United Nations Command in Korea. 
  The pair said they left their duty area at Ochasin-ri, 
Yongyon-kun, South Hwanghae Province, by small boat around 6 
p.m. Jan. 25 to collect fishnets set 50 meters off the coastline 
near their post. 
  But, they were swept away by a sudden gale and went adrift 
before being rescued by a South Korean Naval vessel one mile 
south of the sea boundary around 11:30 a.m. Jan. 27. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

