<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: DPRK `Likely' To Accept Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3101115294 Seoul YONHAP in English 1128 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK3101115294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 31 (YONHAP) -- North Korea is likely to 
accept IAEA (International Atomic Energy Agency) inspections of 
seven declared nuclear facilities and also agree to the 
inter-Korean exchange of special envoys sooner or later, a 
senior South Korean Government official said on Monday. 
  "Though there has been no tangible progress in North 
Korea-IAEA talks in Vienna, we believe North Korea will turn 
affirmative by the time the IAEA Board of Governors meeting 
opens on Feb. 21," he said. 
  The official observed that North Korea now seems trying to 
make most of the inspection issue as a valued "negotiation card" 
in the talks on the nuclear question. 
  He said that the question of inspecting two undeclared 
facilities at Yongbyon would be handled at third-round 
U.S.-North Korea high- level talks. 
  However, if the North Korea-IAEA talks fail, the February 
IAEA Board of Governors meeting would certainly declare that the 
safeguard continuance of the North Korean nuclear facilities was 
broken, in which event the nuclear question woud unavoidably be 
referred to the UN Security Council, he said. 

</TEXT>

