<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chinese Cited on DPRK Efforts To Open Up </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK3101040394 Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN in Korean 31 Jan 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> SK3101040394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [YONHAP from Beijing] </F>
  [Text] According to a Beijing source on 30 January, China 
has noted that North Korea has made political and economic 
changes since the sixth general meeting of the Ninth Supreme 
People's Assembly held in early December 1993. This source well 
versed in the situation of the Korean peninsula and Northeast 
Asia reported: China is paying special attention to the fact 
that North Korea has formed a new South Korean operation team in 
the Workers Party of Korea and appointed Kim Yong-chu, a 
moderate who had been excluded from power for almost 20 years; 
and Kim Tal-hyon, who recently retired from vice premier of the 
State Administration Council, as the top and assistant leaders 
of the team. China is saying that this shows North Korea's will 
to improve relations with Western countries. 
  This sources also said: China views that North Korea's 
agreement with China on a joint promotion to construct indirect 
social capitals in the Najin-Sonbong area and to enlarge and 
develop Chongjin Port forms a link in the chain of its long-term 
policy for opening up. 
  It has been learned that the Chinese view of the North 
Korean 
situation, in particular, was revealed in a classified document 
which was secretly circulated recently among ranking Chinese 
cadres in charge of party policy. 

</TEXT>

