<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Regrets U.S. Rejection of Patent Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2701145994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 26 Jan 
94 Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2701145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Japanese Government is concerned about the 
announcement by the U.S. Department of Commerce that it will not 
change the United States' patent system to a first-to-file 
system. A Patent Office official said: "There is now a 
possibility that the global move toward the patent system 
harmonization will slow down." Member nations of the World 
Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) want to enact a 
"Treaty for Harmonization of Patent Systems," which will unify 
patent systems into a first-to-file system. The Japanese 
Government in the Japan-U.S. framework talks intends to call on 
the U.S. Government to reconsider its stand. 
  The U.S. Government's patent system is the first-to-invent 
system, under which those who invent products first are given 
patent rights, instead of the first-to-file system under which 
those who apply first get the patent right. 
  During the Bush administration, a U.S. Department of 
Commerce 
advisory council recommended changing to the "first-to-file 
system." Given the circumstance, Patent Office officials 
complained: "It is regrettable that the recommendation was 
rejected." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

