<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government: Supercomputer Bidding System Fair </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2701022094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 26 
January 94 Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2701022094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Japanese Government is cool about the results 
on biddings for supercomputer procurement. A Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs [MOFA] official said: "Biddings are held 
fairly. The results merely reflect who are the competitive 
bidders." On the other hand, there are views that the results 
can bring considerably favorable effects on the whole course of 
the deadlocked Japan-U.S. framework talks because the 
governmental procurement biddings issue has been symbolic of 
frictions between Japan and the United States. 
  In 1990, the Japanese Government instituted the procurement 
procedures based on the principle of competitive bidding. A 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry official insisted: 
"Our procurement system treats Japanese and foreign bidders 
completely without discrimination. Therefore, there is no 
problem." Commenting on the results, a MOFA official said: "The 
fact is simple. Competitive bidders have won the bids." 
  Concerning the report that U.S. Cray Research Inc. is 
dissatisfied with the results, a MOFA official said: "The 
reason Cray won fewer computers than it had expected is not 
because there were problems in the procedures but because Cray 
lacked competitiveness." Meanwhile, another official criticized 
Cray's action, saying: "It is unfair to resort to political 
actions." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

