<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Makes Congratulatory Call to Hosokawa </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101083694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0820 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101083694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 31 KYODO -- U.S. President Bill Clinton 
congratulated Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on Monday [31 
January] on his victory in getting political reform bills onto 
the statute books, Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura 
said. In a 15-minute telephone conversation with Hosokawa, 
Clinton said the premier pushed through his reform legislation 
with courage and determination, the top government spokesman 
told a news conference. 
  The government's political reform package cleared the Diet 
on 
Saturday after Hosokawa and Yohei Kono, president of the main 
opposition Liberal Democratic Party, reached a compromise on 
revising it in the regular Diet session, which opened Monday. 
  The reform package is intended to root out graft in Japanese 
politics through a new system for House of Representatives 
elections and stricter controls on campaign funds. 
  Clinton also told Hosokawa that they should both do their 
utmost to make a success of their summit in Washington on 
February 11, Takemura said. 
  The U.S. President reportedly voiced hope that Japan make 
efforts for progress in the bilateral framework trade talks and 
for additional pump-priming measures. The premier, who has 
twice met Clinton, replied he wants to demonstrate his 
leadership in tackling the issues, Takemura said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

