<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Senate Debate on Embargo Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2801155594 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
1430 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2801155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Vietnamese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On the morning of 27 January, the U.S. Senate 
passed with a majority a resolution calling on President Clinton 
to lift the trade embargo against Vietnam to help resolve the 
fate of Americans missing from the Vietnam War. 
  The resolution was submitted by Democratic Senator John 
Kerry 
and Republican Senator John McCain. It was supported by 
senators who are war veterans to pass by a 62 to 38 vote margin. 
Afterwards, the Senate also voted 58 to 42 to reject another 
resolution submitted by Republican Senator Robert Smith 
requesting President Clinton to certify that the Vietnamese 
Government has provided the fullest possible accounting of 
missing Americans before the trade embargo can be lifted. 
  The debate before passing these two resolutions lasted six 
hours on 25 and 26 January. Democratic Senators John Kerry, 
John McCain, and Bob Kerrey stressed that Vietnam is doing its 
best to cooperate with the U.S. in locating missing Americans 
and the U.S. is in danger of losing this cooperation if it 
continues the trade embargo. Other supporters of lifting the 
trade embargo also cited U.S. military personnel working in 
Vietnam who say they are receiving cooperation which they are 
sure will continue with the lifting of the embargo. 
  Senator John McCain also stated that U.S. military personnel 
were working side by side with Vietnamese soldiers to locate 
missing Americans. The cooperation may be terminated if the 
U.S. does not show good cooperation. Senator John Kerry 
believes that the Senate's action will lead to more information 
on missing soldiers and help to close a bitter chapter in 
American history. 
  The senators supporting the resolution calling for lifting 
the trade embargo against Vietnam held that such an action is in 
the best interests of the U.S. as well as Vietnam. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-27783 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas020_d_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-020 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  31 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

