<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Chong-il Sends Birthday Table to Composer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2901110594 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1036 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2901110594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 29 (KCNA) -- Comrade Kim 
Chong-il, supreme commander of the Korean People's Army [KPA], 
sent a sixtieth birthday table to merited artiste Chong 
Tu-myong, a composer of the military band of the Supreme Command 
of the KPA. 
  When Seoul was liberated by the People's Army in the period 
of the fatherland liberation war, Chong, a middle school 
student, joined the People's Army in September 1950 and fought 
bravely before being called to the military band of the Supreme 
Command. 
  He became a composer after graduating from a university. 
Over the last 20 odd years he has composed the welcome music (a 
band music) for major political functions, and hundreds of 
pieces of band music, light music and instrumental concert. 
  Upon receiving the sixtieth birthday table and order of the 
National Flag First Class amid the blessings of his 
comrades-in-arms Friday, Chong Tu-myong said: "I feel the urge 
to go to the South with this table and loudly tell my parents, 
brothers and sisters and South Korean people that this is a 
clear token of the noble love and politics of trust of our dear 
leader Comrade Kim Chong-il for the revolutionary soldiers." 

</TEXT>

