<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kantor Arrives in Tokyo To Discuss Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102091994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0856 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102091994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- U.S. Trade representative 
Mickey Kantor arrived in Tokyo on Tuesday [1 February] in a bid 
to break the deadlock in bilateral trade talks prior to the 
February 11 Washington summit between Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa and President Bill Clinton. Kantor, traveling with W. 
Bowman Cutter, deputy presidential assistant for economic 
policy, is scheduled to meet with Hosokawa, Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata and other key cabinet ministers on Wednesday and 
Thursday. 
  Bilateral negotiations on automobile trade, government 
procurement and other issues have been deadlocked over U.S. 
demands for rules to measure progress in foreign access to 
Japan's markets. The two countries are scheduled to hold 
subcabinet-level negotiations on key pending issues in Tokyo on 
Friday and Saturday. 
  U.S. officials have said Washington hopes that a 
breakthrough 
in the framework trade talks will lead to increased U.S. exports 
to Japan and a significant reduction in Japan's vast trade 
surplus, which last year topped 120 billion dollars worldwide. 

</TEXT>

