<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Told of U.S. `Very Tough Stance' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102124594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1224 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- Japanese Ambassador to the 
United States Takakazu Kuriyama told Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Tuesday [1 February] the United States has taken a 
"very tough stance" in its "framework" economic talks with 
Japan, government officials said. 
  Kuriyama, who is back in Japan temporarily, made the remark 
in discussions with Hosokawa in advance of the prime minister's 
summit talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton on February 11 in 
Washington. 
  Economic issues such as easier U.S. access to Japanese 
Government procurement orders as well as to the auto and 
insurance markets are expected to be high on the summit agenda. 
  Kuriyama, however, was quoted as saying Washington has a 
good 
impression of the cabinet of Hosokawa. 
  Hosokawa staked his political fate on a controversial 
package 
of political reform bills which cleared the Diet on Saturday. 
The four bills introduce major changes in the electoral system 
for the House of Representatives and tighten controls over 
political donations to politicians. 
  In a related development, U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor arrived in Tokyo on Tuesday in an attempt to break the 
deadlock in the bilateral talks prior to the summit talks. 
  Hosokawa will leave for the United States on Thursday night 
and return home Sunday after his meeting with Clinton. 

</TEXT>

