<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Group To Deal With Port Calls by Russians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102032494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0301 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102032494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Asahikawa, Hokkaido, Feb. 1 KYODO -- Fishing 
cooperatives and marine product companies in northern Hokkaido 
formed a new group Tuesday [1 February] to thrash out safety 
measures in light of an increasing number of visits by Russian 
ships. 
  The 27 cooperatives and companies set up a coordinating 
office for the new group in the maritime safety agency's office 
in Wakkanai on the northern tip of Hokkaido. 
  The consultative body will consider safety measures with 
regard to all foreign ships visiting Wakkanai port, but focusing 
on Russian ships. Many of them lack shipowners' liability 
insurance to pay for damages and rescue costs. 
  The group will also distribute Russian language pamphlets, 
noting sites near the port where water is shallow and containing 
information as to where repair work can be carried out. 
  It will also coordinate the quick provision of rescue 
equipment when called for. 
  Visits by Russian ships have rapidly increased in parallel 
with growing contacts between Japanese in Hokkaido, the 
northernmost of Japan's four main islands, and Russians on 
Sakhalin island, which is directly north. 
  Last year, 1,323 foreign ships made port calls at Wakkanai, 
surpassing for the first time the number of such ships visiting 
Otaru, a major Hokkaido port. Some 97 percent of the foreign 
ships visiting Wakkanai were Russian. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-27834 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas021_a_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-021 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nuclear Waste Storage Tanker Plan `Dropped' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102093194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0859 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- Japan and Russia have 
abandoned the use of a chemical tanker for the storage of liquid 
radioactive waste that might otherwise be dumped by the Russian 
Navy into the sea, government officials said Tuesday [1 
February]. The officials said the idea was dropped after it was 
discovered that the used chemical tanker under consideration 
might not be able to withstand the severe cold of the Russian 
Far East. 
  They said the two sides have subsequently begun considering 
the idea of Japan providing financial assistance for emergency 
disposal facilities. 
  Russia asked Japan in talks last December to help find a 
chemical tanker with a storage capacity of between 5,000 tons 
and 25,000 tons. Japan had introduced a 10,000-ton class 
Panamanian-registered tanker docked in Singapore. 
  But Russian inspectors determined that the tanker might not 
be able to withstand severe cold weather conditions and that its 
deck may not be thick enough to prevent adverse effects on the 
environment and on the health of the crew. 
  A 100 million dollar fund pledged by Tokyo to Moscow to help 
it scrap its obsolete nuclear weapons is expected to be utilized 
toward the alternative facilities. 
  Russia last dumped 900 tons of low-level radioactive waste 
into the Sea of Japan on October 17. It suspended a planned 
second dumping following international protests, particularly 
from Japan and South Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

