<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Urges Ukraine To Become Nuclear-Free </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0102095694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0935 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102095694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa has sent a letter to Ukraine President Leonid Kravchuk 
urging that the former Soviet Republic become a nuclear-free 
country as soon as possible, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Terusuke 
Terada said Tuesday [1 February]. Japanese Ambassador to 
Ukraine Shoji Suezawa handed Hosokawa's written message to 
Nikolay Makarevych, Ukraine's first vice foreign minister, 
Terada said. 
  In the letter, Hosokawa gave high marks to a recent 
trilateral accord among Ukraine, Russia and the United States in 
which Ukraine pledged to give up its nuclear arms. He also 
urged Kravchuk to implement the accord as soon as possible, 
Terada said. 
  Hosokawa called on Ukraine to ratify the Strategic Arms 
Reduction Treaty (START I) unconditionally and accede to the 
nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT) as a nonnuclear state, the 
spokesman said. 
  He also said Ukraine's participation in the "Partnership for 
Peace," endorsed by the leaders of North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization (NATO) in Brussels last month, is meaningful in 
enhancing global security. The plan is intended to bring former 
Warsaw Pact adversaries into a limited partnership with the 
Western Military Alliance. 
  Hosokawa's letter also expressed Japan's strong expectations 
that Ukraine will further promote efforts for economic 
development, Terada said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

