<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Places `Massive' Orders for Steel Pipes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101083194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0750 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101083194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 31 KYODO -- Major Japanese steelmakers 
have received a series of Chinese orders for massive imports of 
seamless steel pipes for oil drilling, industry sources said 
Monday [31 January]. 
  China has already ordered about 100,000 tons of the material 
from Nippon Steel Corp., NKK Corp., Sumitomo Metal Industries 
Ltd. and Kawasaki Steel Corp. for deliveries in the 
February-July period, compared with actual shipments of 120,000 
tons a year earlier, they said. 
  There is speculation in the industry that Chinese orders for 
the half year will rise to a level of 150,000 to 200,000 tons. 
  Increased exports in the coming months are likely to bolster 
the Japanese steelmakers' money-losing seamless pipe 
manufacturing operations, the sources said. 
  Despite booming exports of ordinary rolled steel to China, 
Japan's seamless pipe exports to the country have been sluggish 
in recent years, falling to a range of 150,000 to 200,000 tons 
from a peak of about 700,000 tons in the half-year period of 
1985. 
  The sources attributed the active Chinese orders to a series 
of oil development projects in China's inland areas and a 
reduction in Chinese stocks of the material. 
  Japan, which exports more than 70 percent of its seamless 
steel pipe production, has been losing money on the operations 
due to the yen's appreciation on the foreign exchange market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

