<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Announces Loan, Aid to SRV </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2801134294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1111 GMT 28 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2801134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 28 KYODO -- Japan agreed with Vietnam 
on Friday [28 January] to extend a loan of 52.3 billion yen and 
a grant-in-aid of 853 million yen, Foreign Ministry officials 
said. 
  The Japanese Government pledged the loan at an international 
conference on aid to Vietnam held in Paris last November. 
  Japanese Ambassador to Vietnam Hiroyuki Yushita and 
Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam exchanged documents 
on the loan and the grant in Hanoi, the officials said. 
  The loan is for seven projects to improve infrastructure 
related to power supply and transportation, and to pay for 
equipment to repair roads and waterworks, they said. 
  The aid is to support Vietnam's efforts at economic reform 
and to shift to a market-oriented economy under its policy of 
"doi moi" or renovation, they said. 
  Japan will also grant 788 million yen for Can Tho University 
in southern Vietnam to improve its agriculture department. The 
money will be used to build facilities and to pay for equipment. 
  Another grant of 65 million yen will be used for a project 
to 
improve waterworks in northeastern Hanoi. 

</TEXT>

