<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nagoya Court Rejects Refugee Bid by Pakistanis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3101133494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1305 GMT 31 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW3101133494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nagoya, Jan. 31 KYODO -- The Nagoya District Court 
on Monday [31 January] rejected a suit by eight Pakistanis to be 
recognized as refugees, claiming they feared religious 
persecution as members of the minority Ahmadi Sect of Islam if 
forced to return home. 
  Presiding Judge Yoji Okahisa rejected the suit by ruling 
that 
"In Pakistan there is no objective reason to fear persecution, 
so refugee status does not apply." 
  "The domestic situation is such that no criminal penalties 
would be applied aside from using the name of Islam publicly," 
the court decided. 
  The six men and two women had filed suit against the justice 
minister to be recognized as refugees by the Japanese 
Government, saying they feared persecution for their religious 
activities in Pakistan. 
  In 1984, the Pakistani Government pronounced a law that 
prohibited the Ahmadi Sect from identifying itself with Islam 
and including criminal penalties for religious activities. 
  The eight plaintiffs arrived in Japan in 1988 with the help 
of the sect's Nagoya branch office. Claiming that they feared 
being arrested if they returned to Pakistan, the eight applied 
for refugee status with Nagoya immigration authorities, 
receiving an extension to stay in Japan while waiting for a 
decision. Immigration authorities decided, however, there was 
no concrete evidence of persecution. 
  Meanwhile, the extensions to their visas expired while they 
pleaded their case from 1990 to 1992 in a series of suits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

