<F P=102>  OW0102121394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1034 GMT 1 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0102121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb. 1 KYODO -- Japan will extend 10 million 
dollars to cooperate in a United Nations program to reconstruct 
Somalia's police and judicial system, the Foreign Ministry said 
Tuesday [1 February]. 
  Japan pledged the amount at a U.N.-sponsored meeting in 
Nairobi on the establishment of an organization to coordinate 
assistance to Somalia, the ministry said. 
  The government will provide the assistance considering the 
urgent need to reconstruct Somalia's police and judicial system 
and establish a system to maintain public order and restore 
peace by the Somali people themselves, it said. 
  The U.N. Operation in Somalia (UNOSOM II), currently 
deployed 
to maintain the public order and secure safety of humanitarian 
assistance activities, announced last October a program to 
reconstruct the local police and judicial system. 
  The U.N. is calling on member countries to cooperate in the 
program, the ministry said. 

