<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Extends Aid To Help African Refugees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2701093194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0650 GMT 27 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2701093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 27 KYODO -- Japan has disbursed a 
total of 2 million dollars to the World Food Program (WFP) to 
pay for food for refugees in the African nations of Zaire and 
Mauritania, the Foreign Ministry said Thursday [27 January]. 
  The government has extended 1 million dollars to each nation 
to help the refugees through Japan's WFP international emergency 
food reserve, the ministry said. 
  In Mauritania, there are about 50,000 refugees from 
neighboring Mali's Tuareg tribe due to clashes among ethnic 
groups and between the Mali army and the Tuareg tribe, the 
ministry said. 
  In Zaire, there are some 140,000 people who are taking 
refuge 
in the northern region of Kasai because of regional ethnic 
disputes, the ministry said. 

