<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details of Political Reform Package Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901031394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0247 GMT 29 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2901031394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 29 KYODO -- The following were details 
of the political reform compromise package signed early Saturday 
[29 January] between the ruling coalition of Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa and the opposition Liberal Democratic Party. 
The compromise makes it likely the Diet will now approve the 
government's reform bills during its Saturday session. 
<H5>  (House of Representatives) </H5>
  The lower house would have 500 seats, compared with 511 at 
present. This would include 300 from single-seat electoral 
districts and 200 chosen by proportional representation. 
  The coalition originally proposed a combination of 274 
single- seat constituencies and 226 chosen by proportional 
representation. 
<H5>  (Voting) </H5>
  Voters would cast two ballots, one for a single-seat 
representative and another for a party on the proportional list 
divided into 11 regional blocs. 
  The coalition originally proposed candidates for the 
proportional representation seats be chosen from a single 
nationwide list. 
<H5>  (Party Fund-Raising) </H5>
  A politician may designate a single fund-raising 
organization 
to which donations can be paid. Companies may contribute up to 
500,000 yen a year to an organization. The organizations would 
be banned after five years. 
  The coalition originally proposed an immediate ban on 
company 
donations to politicians' support groups. 
<H5>  (Political Parties) </H5>
  A party must poll at least 2 percent of the proportional 
representation vote to qualify to win a seat. 
  Under existing regulations, the figure is 3 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

